= Summary
- Homes in on the (partial) isomorphism existing between the brains of different people.
- Discusses the challenges of translating text and what is most important when doing so.
- Develops an analogy revolving around maps of the USA and the brains of other people.
- Equates consciousness with the symbol (or subsystem) for "the self".
- Describes what makes a thought possible or reasonable.

= Dialogue $arrow.l.r.long$ Chapter Link
The dialogue presents Lewis Carroll's _Jabberwocky_ in three different languages.
The poem is particularly hard to translate due to the connotations of the words, tense, and non-sensical phrases.
However, it can still be translated and evoke similar feeling in readers of different languages because there exist some rough partial isomorphism between the brains of humans regardless of culture or language.
Some translations are more "faithful" than others yet they all have some common ground.
The chapter explores this idea by identifying how brains can be isomorphic with each other and how this relates to symbols and subsystems.

